# Delta-Only Continual Learning Framework
## Full Problem Statement · Build Logic · Theory · References · Usage · What's Still Needed

---

## SECTION 1 — THE ACTUAL PROBLEM (In Plain Words)

Every production ML system eventually faces the same situation.
You trained a model six months ago on everything you had.
New data arrives every day. You need the model to stay accurate.

The brute-force solution is full retraining — retrain from scratch on all old + new data.
This works perfectly. It is also brutally expensive.
If your dataset doubles every year, you are running 2x the compute every cycle.
At Google / Meta / production scale this becomes the dominant infrastructure cost.

The existing alternatives all fail in different ways:

- **Naive incremental learning** (train only on new data, no protection): the model
  catastrophically forgets everything it learned before. Old-class accuracy collapses.

- **Replay / rehearsal methods** (store old samples, mix with new): works but needs
  storage, creates privacy violations (you cannot keep medical or financial data),
  and is illegal in GDPR/HIPAA contexts.

- **EWC / regularisation methods** (penalise changes to important weights): slows
  forgetting but never eliminates it, and gives no quantitative guarantee about how
  bad the forgetting actually gets.

- **Distillation methods** (LwF, iCaRL): need the old model to be alive during new
  training, adds memory overhead, still drifts over many tasks.

**The gap nobody has cleanly filled:**
Can you update a model using ONLY newly arrived data — no stored samples, no old
model in memory — and prove that the result is mathematically equivalent to full
retraining, within a quantifiable error bound?

That is exactly what your PS is asking you to build.

