## SECTION 2 — WHAT YOUR FRAMEWORK NEEDS TO DO (PS Requirements Mapped)

The PS says four things explicitly. Here is each one mapped to a concrete component:

**"updates models using only new data"**
→ Zero-replay delta updater. No historical samples ever loaded.
   Store compressed statistics (means, covariances, Fisher) instead of raw data.

**"matching full retraining performance"**
→ Equivalence verifier. After each update, measure the gap between your delta-trained
   model and a full-retrained model. This gap must be quantifiably small.

**"detect distribution shifts"**
→ Drift detector. Run before and after each update. Catch covariate shift in input
   space and concept drift in embedding space. Output a severity level.

**"correct bias introduced by recent data"**
→ Importance weighter / bias corrector. New data over-represents the recent
   distribution. Re-weight each sample by how likely it was under the full historical
   distribution. This is the core theoretical contribution.

**"quantify equivalence with theoretical bounds"**
→ Formal bound. With probability 1−δ, the accuracy gap between delta-trained and
   full-retrained model is at most ε. Derive this from PAC learning theory applied
   to the importance-weighted loss.

**"significant compute savings"**
→ Benchmark. Show FLOPs ratio, wall-clock time, and accuracy side-by-side.
   The claim needs numbers: e.g. "74% compute reduction with <1% accuracy gap."

