## SECTION 5 — REFERENCE PAPERS AND REPOS

### Must-read papers (in order of importance to your PS)

**1. Sugiyama et al. (2008) — "Direct importance estimation with model selection"**
KLIEP algorithm. This is how you estimate density ratios without old data.
The stored Gaussian statistics from MELD's snapshot are exactly the sufficient
statistics KLIEP needs. This paper gives you the w(x) estimator.
Link: https://proceedings.neurips.cc/paper/2007/hash/be83ab3ecd0db773eb2dc1b0a17836a1-Abstract.html

**2. Cortes et al. (2010) — "Learning bounds for importance weighting"**
Formal PAC bounds for importance-weighted learning. Gives you the ε formula above.
This is the theoretical backbone of your equivalence guarantee.
Link: https://proceedings.neurips.cc/paper/2010/hash/59c33016884a62116be975a9bb8257e3-Abstract.html

**3. Kirkpatrick et al. (2017) — "Overcoming catastrophic forgetting in neural networks"**
The original EWC paper. Explains Fisher information as a curvature proxy and the
quadratic penalty. MELD's updater.py is directly based on this.
Link: https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.1611835114

**4. Lopez-Paz & Ranzato (2017) — "Gradient Episodic Memory for Continual Learning"**
GEM / A-GEM. Shows how to project gradients to not increase old-task loss.
MELD uses PCGrad which is a related idea. This gives the theoretical justification
for gradient projection.
Link: https://arxiv.org/abs/1706.08840

**5. Zenke et al. (2017) — "Continual learning through synaptic intelligence"**
SI method — online importance estimation during training. Useful because MELD
currently only estimates Fisher at snapshot time, not during training.
Link: https://arxiv.org/abs/1703.04200

**6. Hou et al. (2019) — "Learning a Unified Classifier Incrementally via Rebalancing"**
LUCIR / Weight Alignment. This is where MELD's AnalyticNormCorrector comes from.
Important to cite because WA is not the same as importance weighting, and MELD
currently conflates them.
Link: https://openaccess.thecvf.com/content_CVPR_2019/papers/Hou_Learning_a_Unified_Classifier_Incrementally_via_Rebalancing_CVPR_2019_paper.pdf

**7. Zhao et al. (2020) — "Maintaining Discrimination and Fairness in Class Incremental Learning"**
WA paper that directly inspired the norm correction in MELD. Shows why classifier
head bias happens and gives the norm-rescaling fix.
Link: https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.07053

**8. Buzzega et al. (2020) — "Dark Experience for General Continual Learning"**
DER / DER++ — the strongest replay baseline. MELD's avalanche_baselines.py is
supposed to run this but hasn't been wired up yet. You need to beat this.
Link: https://arxiv.org/abs/2004.07211

**9. Wang et al. (2022) — "Learning to Prompt for Continual Learning"**
L2P — transformer-based continual learning. Represents the current SOTA for
class-incremental learning. Your framework should be compared here.
Link: https://arxiv.org/abs/2112.08654

**10. Gretton et al. (2012) — "A Kernel Two-Sample Test"**
MMD (Maximum Mean Discrepancy). This is the theoretical foundation for the
input-space drift detector you need to add. MELD's current KL drift detector
only works on embedding Gaussians. MMD works on raw feature distributions.
Link: https://jmlr.org/papers/v13/gretton12a.html

### Key GitHub repos

**Avalanche** — https://github.com/ContinualAI/avalanche
Your framework should either build on this or at minimum run against its baselines.
Has EWC, LwF, GEM, iCaRL, DER++, A-GEM all implemented with the same evaluation
